eferred to keep silent rather than expose themselves to the animosity of the authorities. Although the fate of Belarusian Jews before and during the war has now been amply studied, this book is one of the first attempts to study Jewish life in Belarus during the last decade of Stalin's rule. In addition to archival materials, the present research is based on a questionnaire submitted to former residents of Belarus in Israel, as well as information from periodicals, collections of documents, statistical reports and monographs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 05. Dez 2022) 0aJews-Belarus-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aBelarus, Ethnic relations, History, Jewish studies, Jews, Political studies, Religion, Soviet Union.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311078054340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633860267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633860267/original  a978-3-11-078054-3  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK